{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"21c106cd-c72e-4977-a6e2-8fe688be0d38","content":"Your project isn't in the current directory, but here's how to configure it. Create or edit `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command`/`args`** — Uses `dotnet run` to build and launch your project.\n- Your server must use **stdio transport** (not HTTP/SSE). If using the `ModelContextProtocol` NuGet package, ensure you call `.WithStdioServerTransport()`.\n- After saving, open the **MCP: List Servers** command in VS Code to verify it connects.\n- You can also place this in your **user-level** `settings.json` under `\"mcp\"` if you want it available across all workspaces.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ae06d347-2a0e-460e-bbc8-28df473fc019","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet, but the user said they built it. They're asking how to configure mcp.json. I can provide guidance based on standard VS Code MCP configuration.","outputTokens":331,"requestId":"700B:1D248C:14F54C8:1828E56:69EC1195"},"id":"34eb89fb-b7b8-49d3-892c-eba38597a3aa","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:58:06.884Z","parentId":"4ae7b038-1dbd-46b2-afbf-c3e1a589a7b5"}
